RNA Sequencing of the Human Milk Fat Layer Transcriptome Reveals Distinct Gene Expression Profiles at Three Stages of Lactation

Nikola Panajotovikj, Ester Muñoz del Campo, Marko Ludaic1

1Universitat Pompeu Fabra

2023-06-14

1 Introduction

Because of the numerous benefits breastfeeding provides, it’s recommended that infants be exclusively breastfed for the first 6 months with continued breastfeeding for at least 1 year. However lactation is not achieved in all mothers and the physiology of this process remains poorly understood. This is because of questions related to the ethics of performing tests or extracting tissues from lactating mother.

So, an interesting alternative has been proposed – human milk secreted during lactation is a rich source of mammary epithelial cell RNA. About 3–8% of human milk fat globules contain mammary epithelial cell cytoplasmic remnants, including RNA, captured during milk fat globule formation and secretion

Previous to this research, there has been attempt to undestand the human milk fat layer transcriptome with microarray techniques (Maningat et al. 2009). This paper analyses the transcriptome with RNA-seq which, compared to microarray, has highly sensitive detail, can accurately quantify both very low and very high abundance transcripts, as well as detect novel transcripts.

The authors of this paper (Lemay et al. 2013), furthermore, suggest that the constitution of the human milk is not dependent on the days postpartum, which is the measure typically used by lactation researchers to categorize lactation stage. Rather, they state that compared to other factors such as subject, washing protocol, or time of collection, biochemically defined lactation stage (i.e., Na:K) has the largest effect on the transcriptome. So they categorise the samples as: “colostral” if Na:K >= 2.0; and as “transitional” if Na:K < 2.0; “mature” if Na:K < 0.6 .

The three main challanges of this paper are:

  • because of the sample extraction, it is unknown if the milk fat layer yields RNA purely of mammary epithelial cell origin, or if RNA from non-mammary epithelial sources is also present in the milk fat layer obtained from colostrum, transitional, or mature human milk,

  • because of the body heat and the environment of the milk, the RNA might end up being degraded (low RIN values),

  • because this is a study of patients who would agree to participate after just having gone through giving birth and have to fulfill some criteria, the sample size is very small which is something that really influences the information that can be extracted and extrapolated from this sample group - the result of bias of such a small sample group is really apparent in the MA-plots

In the output above we can observe the columns containing groups of data values, that means excluding the columns presenting the same value for all samples or a different value for each sample. We can see that there are:

  • patients that are repeated because their milk was sampled in 2 or 3 of the 3 stages of lactation reported in the paper (id numbers: 179, 183, 187).

  • given the different 3 stages, 3 groups of samples appear (this is a biologically relevant factor): Colostrum lactation stage; Mature lactation stage; Transitional lactation stage.

  • because of the different protocols there are 4 different groups (technically relevant) Hard spin, Unwashed ; Hard spin, Washed once ; Hard spin, Washed twice ; Soft spin, Unwashed.

To facilitate handling these variables we are going to recode them as follows.

First we replace spaces in column names.

# simpler names
names(colData(se))[37] <- "id"
names(colData(se))[36] <- "lacStage"
names(colData(se))[35] <- "protocol"

# creating factors
colData(se)$idFac <- factor(colData(se)$id)
# colData(se)$lacStageFac <- factor(colData(se)$lacStage)
colData(se)$lacStageFac <- factor(colData(se)$lacStage,
                                  levels = c("Colostrum", "Transitional", "Mature"),
                                  labels = c(1, 2, 3))

#colData(se)$protocolFac <- factor(colData(se)$protocol)
colData(se)$protocolFac <- factor(colData(se)$protocol,
                                  levels = c("Soft spin, Unwashed", "Hard spin, Unwashed", "Hard spin, Washed once", "Hard spin, Washed twice"),
                                  labels = c(1, 2, 3, 4 ))

2.2 Sequencing depth

Let’s examine the sequencing depth in terms of total number of sequence read counts mapped to the genome per sample. The figure below shows the sequencing depth per sample, also known as library sizes, in increasing order.

From the plot above we don’t notice any biases related to the different lactation stages (colors). The only thing that stands out is SRR801705 as having very low sequencing depth. In the later part of the analysis we will remove it from the analysis, since it seems to be an error with the sample sequencing.

From the plot above we do not see any bias. The “Hard spin, Washed once” groups together but there doesn’t seem to be a significantly extreme difference in their sequencing depth. We will further analyze this with a clustering approach.

2.3 Distribution of expression levels among samples

Figure 1 below shows the distribution of expression values per sample in logarithmic CPM units of expression.

Figure 1: Non-parametric density distribution of expression profiles per sample

There are no substantial differences between the samples in the distribution of expression values.

par(mar=c(7, 5, 2, 2))
boxplot(assays(se)$logCPM, col="gray", ylab=expression(log[2] * "CPM"),
cex.axis=1.2, cex.lab=1.5, las=2)

In the previous plots we see that the SRR801705 sample does not behave differently than the rest, but this is due to the fact that we are now considering the counts per million (CPM), and what is wrong about that sample is the sequencing depth, so still we will exclude it from the analysis.

2.4 Distribution of expression levels among genes

Let’s calculate now the average expression per gene through all the samples. Figure 2 shows the distribution of those values across genes.

Figure 2: Distribution of average expression level per gene

As expected, we have two modes, one for genes that are lowly expressed in nearly all samples and another for genes with some detectable levels of expression across a number of samples.

2.5 Filtering of lowly-expressed genes

In the paper, transcript abundances were estimated as FPKMs (fragments per kilobase of exon per million fragments mapped) using Cufflinks. Genes with a mean expression level less than 0.01 FPKM (manually set) across all time points and all samples were excluded from further analysis.

In our analysis, we use CPM (counts per million) and after some trial and error we found that the best cutoff value from the cpm would be arround 0.1.


#cpmcutoff <- round(10/min(dge_sample_filtered$sample$lib.size/1e6), digits=1)
cpmcutoff <- 0.1
print(cpmcutoff)
[1] 0.1

#nsamplescutoff <- min(table(se_sample_filtered$protocolFac))
nsamplescutoff<- 15 
print(nsamplescutoff)
[1] 15

mask <- rowSums(cpm(dge_sample_filtered) > cpmcutoff) >= nsamplescutoff

se.filt <- se_sample_filtered[mask, ]
dim(se.filt)
[1] 11729    15
dge.filt <- dge_sample_filtered[mask, ]
dim(dge.filt)
[1] 11729    15



par(mar=c(4, 5, 1, 1))

h <- hist(avgexp, xlab=expression("Expression level (" * log[2] * "CPM)"), 
          main="", las=1, col="grey", cex.axis=0.95, cex.lab=1.2)

x <- cut(rowMeans(assays(se.filt)$logCPM), breaks=h$breaks)

lines(h$mids, table(x), type="h", lwd=10, lend=1, col="darkred")

legend("topright", c("All genes", "Filtered genes"), fill=c("grey", "darkred"))

We are left with 11729 genes.

2.6 Normalization

We calculate now the normalization factors on the filtered expression data set.

dge.filt <- calcNormFactors(dge.filt)

Replace the raw log2 CPM units in the corresponding assay element of the SummarizedExperiment object, by the normalized ones.

assays(se.filt)$logCPM <- cpm(dge.filt, log=TRUE,
                              normalized.lib.sizes=TRUE)

2.7 MA-plots

We examine now the MA-plots of the normalized expression profiles in Figure 3.

Figure 3: MA-plots of filtered and normalized expression values

A number of samples display some expression-level dependent bias. For cases in which this occurs at the low-end of the expression level, one solution could be to have a more stringent filter on minimum expression using a grouping with more samples per group, for instance. However, considering the low number of samples we are working with we decide to keep it this way. Of course, we should keep an eye on samples with these biases in case they also display other unexpected features, because then we might consider removing them.

2.8 Experimental design and batch identification

Here try to understand the underlying experimental design. We take a look at the combination of sample preparation protocol and lactation stage.

table(se.filt$lacStageFac, se.filt$protocolFac)
   
    1 2 3 4
  1 0 1 2 0
  2 1 1 3 0
  3 1 2 1 3

We can see that not all the protocols have been used in all lactation stages, but still the distribution is quite balanced and the number of missing combinations is not critical for the analysis. This means that there are more chances that the differences observed are due to biological reasons rather than technical.

We examine now how samples group together by hierarchical clustering and multidimensional scaling, annotating lactation stage (number) and protocol(color) for each sample. We calculate again log CPM values with a high prior count(3) to moderate extreme fold-changes produced by low counts. The resulting dendrogram is shown in Figure 4.

Figure 4: Hierarchical clustering of the samples by technical factor - protocol used

We can see that the samples do not seem to group by protocol. Now we will test if they group by lactation stage in the Figure 5.

Figure 5: Hierarchical clustering of the samples by biological factor - lactation stage

We can clearly see that the samples group by lactation stage in the clustering, since each cluster contains samples from a lactation stage, with the only exception of the sample SRR801691.

Next we will perform an MDS plot using the names of the lactation stages and colors according to protocol in order to ratify if they in deed group by lactation stage (Figure ??).

outcome <- se.filt$lacStage
batch <- as.integer(se.filt$protocolFac)
names(outcome) <- colnames(se.filt)
plotMDS(dge.filt, labels=outcome, col=batch)
legend("topright", levels(se.filt$protocolFac),
       fill=seq_len(nlevels(se.filt$protocolFac)), inset=0.05, 
       legend=c("Soft spin, Unwashed", "Hard spin, Unwashed", "Hard spin, Washed once", "Hard spin, Washed twice"))

In fact, the samples group by lactation stage.

3 Differential expression

We now perform an analysis to observe differential expressed (DE) genes by excluding each of the 3 lactation stages one by one. This is also the approach that is described in the paper.

3.1 Analysing Fold-Change

Col_exp <- rowMeans(logCPM[, se_sample_filtered$lacStage=="Colostrum"])
Tra_exp <- rowMeans(logCPM[, se_sample_filtered$lacStage=="Transitional"])
Mat_exp <- rowMeans(logCPM[, se_sample_filtered$lacStage=="Mature"])

Given that the sample size is small, the fold-change plots have wider distribution - because of this we also expect to end up with more DE genes in the DE analysis later.

In Figure 6 we analyse the fold-change for the Colostral and Transitional stage.

plot((Tra_exp+Col_exp)/2, Tra_exp-Col_exp, pch=".", cex=4, las=1)

Figure 6: A plot analysing the difference in expression between Colostral and Transitional stage

In Figure 7 we analyse the fold-change for the Colostral and Mature stage.

plot((Mat_exp+Col_exp)/2, Mat_exp-Col_exp, pch=".", cex=4, las=1)

Figure 7: A plot analysing the difference in expression between Colostral and Mature stage

In Figure 8 we analyse the fold-change for the Transitional and Mature stage.

plot((Mat_exp+Tra_exp)/2, Mat_exp-Tra_exp, pch=".", cex=4, las=1)

Figure 8: A plot analysing the difference in expression between Transitional and Mature stage

From the three plots above (Figures 6, 7, 8), we can see that when Colostrum is compared with another stage the difference in expression is greater, than when we compare Transitional and Mature (Figure 8).

3.2 Performing Differential Expression (DE)

First, we will observed stage 1 and 2 that correspond to colostrum and transitional stage, leaving out the maturation stage (stage 3). Afterwards, we will exclude colostrum stage (stage 1) and finally we will exclude transitional stage (stage 2). We do the same scheme later for the functional enrichment analysis.

It’s worth mentioning that because with the noise from the low sample size, we end up with a lot of DE genes. To reduce the number of genes and to increase the validity of the DE analysis we perform two DE analysis: one with SVA and one with limma - then we extract the intersection of both those sets. We use this later on for the functional enrichment.

library(sva)
library(limma)

3.3 DE Between Colostrum and Transitional

Checking the distribution of differentially expressed genes. In Figure 9 we analyse the differential expression between the Colostrum and Transitional stage.

se.filt.all <- se.filt[,se.filt$lacStageFac!=3]
se.filt.all$stage <- droplevels(se.filt.all$lacStageFac)

mod <- model.matrix(~ se.filt.all$stage, colData(se.filt.all))

Figure 9: P-value diagnostic plot for differental expression between Colostrum and Transitional

mask <- p.adjust(pv, method="fdr") < 0.1

3.6 Summary of DE

The number of DE genes in the three comparisons above are:

  • Colostral-Transitional 7190 DE genes
  • Transitional-Mature 2364 DE genes
  • Colostral-Mature 9013 DE genes.

It is evident that the number of differentially expressed genes that was obtained in each of the three analysis is quite in line with the number that was reported in the paper. There the observed numbers in the paper are 8015, 1948 and 8527 respectively - correlation value with our findings 0.9803616. These numbers are quite large and we think it makes sense because of the nature of the tissue, since the milk should adapt to the infant’s needs.

As we mentioned, the sample size is quite small in our case, so that gives rise to different biases which can be dealt with using different strategies, and yielding slightly different results.

4 Functional analysis (FA)

library(org.Hs.eg.db)
library(GOstats)
library(KEGGREST)

geneUniverse <- rownames(se)

In this part we will perform the functional analysis (FA). The scheme of the analysis is similar to the DE analysis. First, we will observe stage 1 and 2 that correspond to colostrum and transitional stage, leaving out the mature stage (stage 3). Afterwards, we will exclude colostrum stage (stage 1) and finally we will exclude transitional stage (stage 2).

For each of the compared stages we will perform 2 FAs: one for GO enrichment and another for KEGG enrichment. The reasons for also doing a KEGG analysis are two: (1) Following what the authors did in the paper. (2) GO enrichment analyzes gene sets based on functional annotations from the Gene Ontology, covering a wide range of biological processes - this leaves us with a huge list of enriched pathways. Whereas, KEGG enrichment specifically focuses on identifying overrepresented pathways from the Kyoto Encyclopedia of Genes and Genomes, resulting in a narrower set of enriched pathways compared to the broader functional annotations provided by GO.

Finally, for each pair of stages, we will also look at the the top 7 fold-change genes previously extracted and their presence in the enriched gene sets. (This is more of an analysis that we simply did becuase of interest in how much the enrichemnt is related to the fold-change of a gene.)

4.1 Between Colostrum and Transitional

4.1.1 GO enrichment

params <- new("GOHyperGParams", geneIds=DEgenesEGs_no3, 
              universeGeneIds=geneUniverse, annotation="org.Hs.eg.db", 
              ontology="BP", pvalueCutoff=0.05, testDirection="over")

conditional(params) <- TRUE
hgOverCond <- hyperGTest(params)
goresults <- summary(hgOverCond)

With some trial and error, we decided to set the size to be [3, 100] and the count >= 25. The size represents the number of genes in the GO terms, and the count is the number of genes that we calculate as DE. This way we include the important but not too general pathways; we are furthermore including only the pathways that have a high number of DE genes in the dataset, ei. the gene sets that are highly enriched.

mask <- goresults$OddsRatio != "Inf"
goresults <- goresults[mask, ]
goresults <- goresults[order(goresults$OddsRatio, decreasing=TRUE), ]
goresults <- goresults[goresults$Size >= 3 & goresults$Size <= 100 & goresults$Count >=25, ]
geneIDs <- geneIdsByCategory(hgOverCond)[goresults$GOBPID]
geneSYMs <- sapply(geneIDs, function(id) select(org.Hs.eg.db, columns="SYMBOL", key=id, keytype="ENTREZID")$SYMBOL)
geneSYMs <- sapply(geneSYMs, paste, collapse=", ")
goresults <- cbind(goresults, Genes=geneSYMs)
rownames(goresults) <- 1:nrow(goresults)

5 Discussion

5.1 Interpreting findings of DE and FA between Colostrum and Transitional

The first most significant hit in the KEGG Enrichment table made by comparing Colostrum and Transitional stage suggest that Lipid Metabolism is quite important in the first stage of lactation (6). The corresponding term for this KEGG class name is fatty acid biosynthesis which indicates that the early synthesis of fatty acids is crucial and beneficial for the milk production. Literature suggest that breastfeeding has a fundamental role in nourishing offspring by supplying a lipid-rich product that is used to create heat and metabolic fuel. Lipids are therefore a necessity for the newborn mammals since they provide heat mediated by the uncoupling of mitochondrial respiration in specific fat depots(Röszer 2021). Additionally, fatty acid elongation has been found as significant KEGG term for the same lactation stage along with glycosphingolipid biosynthesis and aminosugar and nucleotide sugar metabolism.

5.2 Interpreting findings of DE and FA between Transitional and Mature

Protein localization to endoplasmic reticulum is the most significant GO Enrichment term in DE analysis between Transitional and Mature lactation stages (9) Scientific research (Honvo-Houéto et al. 2016) suggest that this is connected with the importance of casein transport, a family of related phosphoproteins that are commonly found in mammalian milk and are synthesized and transported along the secretory pathway and released by exocytosis. Endoplasmic reticulum and the secretory vesicles contribute significantly to the milk fat globule membrane formation and since caseins are secreted by exocytosis there is a need for generating a stable molecular transport system. Second most significant GO term is described as endoplasmic reticulum organization which additionally confirms the importance of this organelle between these two lactation stages.

KEGG Enrichment between Transitional and Mature lactation stages (10) didn’t show much difference in comparison to the previous group. It is evident that biosynthesis of glycosphinoglipids and unsaturated fatty acid is still very important with the addition of steroid biosynthesis. A study from 2018 (Hamdan et al. 2018) determined the contents of sterols in the pools of colostrum, transitional and up to 6-month old human milk. Their results showed that the sterol content varies depending on the lactation stage with the highest bio-accessibility in the first lactation stage.

5.3 Interpreting findings of DE and FA between Colostrum and Mature

GO Enrichment in this groups (Table 13) showed regulation of autophagy of mitochondrion as a number one GO term. Extreme starvation induces the intracellular recycling of nutrients in order to sustain energy resources and life. Although excessive starvation itself is destructive, the induction of autophagy is required for recycling of intracellular contents to maintain energetic homeostasis under restricted nutrient conditions (Webster et al. 2014) The absolute requirement of this intracellular recycling for energetic homeostasis is evident in neonates during the postpartum period where the initial maternal production of milk is insufficient for the infant’s energy needs (Kuma et al. 2004). This would suggest that maternal genes could provide products that are regulators of autophagy and are therefore needed in order to ensure the neonates homeostasis once the autophagy begins.

5.4 Cross-referencing with the given article

In comparison with the article (Lemay et al. 2013) we find similar results.

5.4.1 Comparing Colostral with the two other

We also find an DE genes of (iso)ferritins (FTL, FTH1) with enrichment in the GO term “iron ion homeostasis”. Furthermore, glycosylation and other sugar modifications are also present (KEGG terms: Glycosphingolipid biosynthesis - globo and isoglobo series, Glycosaminoglycan degradation, Glycosylphosphatidylinositol (GPI)-anchor biosynthesis, Glycan degradation). This processes are probably related to immune functions - antimicrobial role (Christensen et al. 2010).

Moreover, several catabolic processes are functionally enriched, suggesting natural pre-digestion of milk proteins (Dallas et al. 2013). (Tables 5, 6, 13, 14)

5.4.2 Comparing Transitional with the two other

In this stage, we also find that there is an increase in the translational activity and overall ribosomal proteins (KEGG terms: Ribosome, Protein export; GO term: translational initiation). (Tables 5, 6, 9, 10)

5.4.3 Comparing Mature with the two other

Finally, in this stage, we also notice the DE of CSN2, a gene encoding milk casein (b-casein) with the GO term “lactation” (Table 13).

6 Conclusions

Not all lactating mothers report that they have achieved their desired amount of breastfeeding for the newborn – they usually include supplements and synthetic milk in the baby’s diet. Breastfeeding provides many benefits, however the physiology of this process remains poorly understood, because of ethical concerns about experimental procedures on breastfeeding mothers. To work around this issue, this paper takes a similar approach to a previous study (Maningat et al. 2009) using micro-array technology, where they isolate RNA from the milk. Moreover, this study is important because it establishes protocols for extracting RNA from milk and processing it for RNA-sequencing technology.

Furthermore, the authors show that, contrary to previous medical belief, the lactational stages do not cluster according to days postpartum, but according to one important biochemical parameter – the ratio of Na:K content. The authors suggest three stages of milk secretion: Colostral (Na:K >= 2.0;), Transitional (Na:K < 2.0) and Mature (Na:K < 0.6).

When analyzing the MA-plots (Figure 3) we found that some samples displayed expression-level dependent bias. This goes hand-in-hand with the fact that: * because of the sample extraction, it is unknown if the milk fat layer yields RNA purely of mammary epithelial cell origin, or if RNA from non-mammary epithelial sources is also present in the milk fat layer obtained from colostrum, transitional, or mature human milk, and * because of the body heat and the environment of the milk, RNA might end up being degraded (low RIN values).

Moreover, when we looked at the experimental design and batch identification we could only find one potential batch factor – the protocol used for RNA extraction. However, using hierarchical clustering (Figures 4, 5) and a multidimensional scaling plot (Figure ??) we saw that samples did not group by this technical factor, but rather they grouped by the stage of lactation.

From the obtained results, it is evident that there is a high need for establishing a good immune defense system during the colostral stage of lactation and the production of lipids should be also finished during the mature stage of lactation. During the transitional stage, the up-regulation of massive milk protein synthesis and organization seems to be the most important task. Such results indicate that it is possible to define a lactation stage based on biochemical parameters from RNA expression profiles and these findings are in line with the reported results from the given article (Lemay et al. 2013) .
